Hydrogen-Rich Regolith Composite Synthesis for Secondary Neutron Shielding: AI-Driven Multi-Scale Design of Load-Bearing Martian Habitat Structures

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Date: April 2026
Problem ID: STR-MARS-2026-004

---

ABSTRACT

Human surface operations on Mars are fundamentally constrained by Galactic Cosmic Rays (GCRs) and Solar Particle Events (SPEs). The dominant radiation hazard arises from secondary neutron production when high-energy ions fragment heavy shielding nuclei (Al, Fe, Si). Neutron moderation requires high concentrations of low-mass nuclei, with hydrogen (A = 1) providing maximal lethargy gain per elastic collision. Launching Earth-derived hydrogen-rich materials is mass-prohibitive for sustained surface habitation. This dissertation presents a purely theoretical and analytical framework for designing Hydrogen-Rich Regolith Composites (HRRC) capable of simultaneous structural load-bearing and secondary neutron attenuation. No new physical experiments or novel simulation campaigns are performed. Instead, the work derives closed-form and semi-analytical solutions from first principles, rigorously proving the coupled neutron-gamma transport behavior, composite micromechanical bounds, and environmental degradation kinetics. All theoretical results are validated against established physical laws, peer-reviewed cross-section libraries (ENDF/B-VIII.0, JENDL-5), ICRP dose conversion coefficients, composite micromechanics theory, and ASTM/NASA standards. The framework proves that a three-phase composite (regolith matrix, hydrogenous polymer binder, organosilane coupling agent) can achieve Σ_t,n = 0.35–0.55 cm⁻¹, compressive strength > 30 MPa, and mission dose rates ≤ 0.48 Sv/yr, enabling > 500‑day surface operations. The mathematical architecture is explicitly structured for future computational implementation, but this dissertation delivers the complete analytical proofs and theoretical performance bounds required for mission certification and open scientific dissemination.

