CHAPTER 1: INTRODUCTION & THEORETICAL PROBLEM STATEMENT

1.1 The Martian Radiation Environment

Mars lacks a global magnetosphere and possesses a thin CO₂ atmosphere (P_surf ≈ 610 Pa, column density ≈ 16 g/cm²). The unattenuated GCR flux at solar minimum is approximately 3–5 particles cm⁻² s⁻¹, dominated by protons (85%), alpha particles (14%), and high-Z nuclei (1%). GCR intensities, and subsequently the radiation dose on the Martian surface, are highest during solar minimum and lowest during solar maximum. When these ions interact with habitat materials, nuclear spallation produces secondary neutrons (0.1 MeV ≤ E_n ≤ 1 GeV). Neutrons are electrically neutral and interact primarily via elastic/inelastic scattering and radiative capture, causing severe biological damage (high-LET secondary protons, DNA double-strand breaks) and Single Event Upsets (SEUs) in microelectronics.

1.2 The Hydrogen Moderation Imperative

Neutron energy loss per elastic collision is governed by the target nucleus mass number A. Hydrogen (A = 1) maximizes kinetic energy transfer, thermalizing fast neutrons in fewer collisions. Shielding efficacy scales with hydrogen number density n_H, not areal mass alone. The relevant figure of merit is the macroscopic slowing-down power ξΣ_s.

1.3 Research Gap & Theoretical Objectives

Current ISRU shielding concepts (regolith berming, polyethylene liners) fail to satisfy the triad of requirements: (1) high neutron attenuation, (2) structural integrity under 1 atm internal pressure, and (3) in-situ manufacturability. Previous theoretical treatments have neglected the coupled neutron-gamma transport problem and have not rigorously bounded polymer stability under Martian perchlorate oxidation and vacuum outgassing.

This dissertation addresses these gaps through purely analytical derivations. The research questions are answered by constructing a deductive mathematical framework:

1. Derive and prove the macroscopic transport parameters for a multi-phase regolith-polymer composite.
2. Prove the necessity of coupled neutron-gamma transport and establish analytical dose bounds.
3. Derive composite micromechanical strength and interfacial shear bounds from first principles.
4. Formulate and solve the multi-objective optimization problem analytically, proving Pareto optimality conditions.

CHAPTER 2: NUCLEAR TRANSPORT & MODERATION PROOFS

2.1 Proposition: Macroscopic Cross‑Section Additivity

Statement.
For a multi‑phase composite with non‑overlapping, homogenously distributed phases, the effective macroscopic total cross‑section is the volume‑weighted sum of the constituent macroscopic cross‑sections.

Proof.
Let the composite consist of n distinct phases. Phase i occupies volume fraction \phi_i (\sum_i \phi_i = 1) and has atomic number density N_i (atoms/cm³). The microscopic total cross‑section of phase i at neutron energy E is \sigma_{t}^{(i)}(E). The macroscopic cross‑section of the pure phase is \Sigma_i(E) = N_i \sigma_{t}^{(i)}(E).

Over a distance dx, the probability that a neutron interacts in phase i is \Sigma_i \phi_i dx, because the neutron’s path through the composite encounters phase i with probability \phi_i and, when in that phase, interacts with probability \Sigma_i dx. The total interaction probability is the sum over all phases:

dP_{\text{total}} = \sum_{i=1}^n \Sigma_i \phi_i \, dx \equiv \Sigma_{\text{eff}} \, dx .

Hence

\boxed{ \Sigma_{\text{eff}}(E) = \sum_{i=1}^n \phi_i \, \Sigma_i(E) } .

For a composite whose phases are chemical mixtures, the same additivity holds after expressing \Sigma_i from the mass fractions of elements. With bulk density \rho_{\text{comp}} and mass fraction w_j of element j (atomic mass M_j, microscopic cross‑section \sigma_{t}^{(j)}),

\Sigma_{\text{eff}} = \rho_{\text{comp}} N_A \sum_{j} \frac{w_j}{M_j} \, \sigma_{t}^{(j)}(E) ,

where N_A is Avogadro’s number. This is the standard mixture rule (Duderstadt & Hamilton, 1976), exact when the characteristic inclusion size d is much smaller than the neutron mean free path \lambda_n (for 1–10 MeV neutrons, \lambda_n \approx 2–5 cm; here d \sim 50\ \mum, so d \ll \lambda_n). Resonances that could violate additivity are treated separately in §2.5.

