2.2 Proposition: Maximum Lethargy Gain for Hydrogen (A=1)

Statement.
Hydrogen (mass number A=1) gives the highest possible average logarithmic energy loss per elastic collision, \xi = 1.

Proof.
For elastic scattering on a stationary nucleus of mass number A, the average logarithmic energy loss (lethargy gain) is

\xi = 1 + \frac{(A-1)^2}{2A} \ln\!\left(\frac{A-1}{A+1}\right) .

Define \alpha = \left(\frac{A-1}{A+1}\right)^2. An equivalent form is \xi = 1 - \frac{(A-1)^2}{2A} \ln \alpha. For A=1, \alpha = 0 and the logarithm diverges; the limit must be taken. Evaluate using L’Hôpital’s rule:

\lim_{A\to 1} \xi = 1 + \lim_{A\to 1} \frac{(A-1)^2 \ln\!\left(\frac{A-1}{A+1}\right)}{2A}.

Set x = A-1, then x\to 0 and \frac{x-1}{x+1} = \frac{x}{x+2}. The numerator becomes x^2 \ln\!\left(\frac{x}{x+2}\right) = x^2 \bigl(\ln x - \ln(x+2)\bigr). As x\to0, \ln x \to -\infty, but multiplied by x^2 the product tends to 0 (since x^2 \ln x \to 0). Hence the whole fraction tends to 0, and \xi \to 1. For any A>1, \xi = \frac{2}{A+2/3} (a good approximation). Since \xi strictly decreases with A, the maximum is at A=1:

\boxed{ \xi_{\max} = 1 } .

The number of collisions to thermalise a neutron from initial energy E_0 to thermal energy E_{\text{th}} is

n = \frac{\ln(E_0/E_{\text{th}})}{\xi}.

For E_0 = 2\ \text{MeV}, E_{\text{th}} = 0.025\ \text{eV}, \ln(E_0/E_{\text{th}}) = \ln(8\times10^7) \approx 18.2. Thus
n_{\text{H}} = 18.2,
n_{\text{C}} \approx 18.2 / 0.158 \approx 115,
n_{\text{Fe}} \approx 18.2 / 0.0353 \approx 516.

Hydrogen reduces the required collisions by more than an order of magnitude compared to iron, proving the “hydrogen imperative”.

