2.3 Macroscopic Slowing‑Down Power and Moderation Length

The macroscopic slowing‑down power (energy loss per unit path length) is

\Xi = \xi \, \Sigma_s ,

where \Sigma_s is the macroscopic scattering cross‑section. For a composite, \Sigma_s also follows the volume additivity rule (§2.1). The Fermi age (moderation length) \tau to thermal energy is

\tau = \int_{E_{\text{th}}}^{E_0} \frac{D(E)}{\xi \Sigma_s(E)} \frac{dE}{E},

with D(E) the diffusion coefficient. For hydrogen‑rich media, \tau is minimised because \xi \Sigma_s is large.

