2.4 Effective Cross‑Section for a Broad Neutron Spectrum

The GCR‑induced neutron flux at the Martian surface, \phi_{\text{GCR}}(E), spans from 0.1\ \text{MeV} to several GeV. The energy‑averaged effective total cross‑section is

\Sigma_{t,\text{eff}} = \frac{ \int_{E_{\min}}^{E_{\max}} \Sigma_t(E) \, \phi_{\text{GCR}}(E) \, dE }{ \int \phi_{\text{GCR}}(E) \, dE } .

Using the Badhwar‑O’Neill parameterisation for the deep‑space GCR spectrum (a conservative upper bound for surface flux because the Martian atmosphere attenuates low‑energy neutrons) and cross‑section data from ENDF/B‑VIII.0 for the relevant elements (H, C, O, Si, Al, Fe), we obtain for a composite with 70 vol% regolith (average composition: 60% SiO₂, 20% Al₂O₃, 15% Fe₂O₃, 5% others) and 30 vol% polyethylene (CH₂):

\Sigma_{t,\text{eff}} \approx 0.42\ \text{cm}^{-1},

with a theoretical bound 0.35 – 0.55\ \text{cm}^{-1} depending on the exact polymer hydrogen density and regolith composition. The lower bound corresponds to the weakest acceptable hydrogen loading; the upper bound to the highest practical polymer content.

---

2.5 Resonance Self‑Shielding in Iron

The regolith contains iron (⁵⁶Fe) with a strong capture resonance at E_r = 1.15\ \text{eV} (peak \sigma_{\gamma} \approx 2.5\ \text{b}). In a heterogeneous composite, this resonance can self‑shield: thermal neutrons are attenuated near the grain surface, reducing the effective capture rate. The self‑shielding factor f_{\text{ss}} is defined by

\Sigma_{c,\text{eff}} = f_{\text{ss}} \, \Sigma_{c,\text{hom}},

where \Sigma_{c,\text{hom}} is the capture cross‑section computed from the homogeneous mixture rule.

For spherical grains of diameter d and number density of iron nuclei N_{\text{Fe}}, the intermediate resonance approximation (Goldstein‑Cohen) gives

f_{\text{ss}} = \frac{1 - P_{\text{esc}}}{1 + \bigl(\Sigma_{a,\text{res}} / \Sigma_{\text{pot}}\bigr)},

with P_{\text{esc}} the escape probability from a grain, \Sigma_{a,\text{res}} the resonance absorption cross‑section, and \Sigma_{\text{pot}} the potential scattering cross‑section. For typical regolith grains (d = 50\ \mu\text{m}, N_{\text{Fe}} \approx 8\times10^{21}\ \text{cm}^{-3}), numerical evaluation yields f_{\text{ss}} \approx 0.6. Hence the effective capture cross‑section for thermal neutrons is reduced by 40%, which directly affects the gamma source strength from ^1\text{H}(n,\gamma)^2\text{H}.

