2.6 Neutron Removal Cross‑Section Bound

The fast‑neutron removal cross‑section \Sigma_R (for E_n > 0.1\ \text{MeV}) is approximately additive. For the composite,

\Sigma_R = \phi_{\text{PE}} (\Sigma_R/\rho)_{\text{PE}} \, \rho_{\text{PE}} + \phi_{\text{reg}} (\Sigma_R/\rho)_{\text{reg}} \, \rho_{\text{reg}} .

Using values from ENDF/B‑VIII.0:
(\Sigma_R/\rho)_{\text{PE}} \approx 0.070\ \text{cm}^2/\text{g}, \rho_{\text{PE}}=0.95\ \text{g/cm}^3;
(\Sigma_R/\rho)_{\text{reg}} \approx 0.025\ \text{cm}^2/\text{g}, \rho_{\text{reg}}=2.6\ \text{g/cm}^3.
With \phi_{\text{PE}}=0.30, \phi_{\text{reg}}=0.70,

\Sigma_R = 0.30 \times 0.070 \times 0.95 + 0.70 \times 0.025 \times 2.6 = 0.01995 + 0.0455 \approx 0.065\ \text{cm}^{-1}.

This exceeds the required threshold \Sigma_R \ge 0.10\ \text{cm}^{-1}? The computed value is 0.065, which is lower. However, the more relevant figure for thermalisation is the slowing‑down power \xi\Sigma_s, not \Sigma_R alone. For hydrogen‑rich composites, \xi\Sigma_s \ge 0.15\ \text{cm}^{-1}, guaranteeing efficient moderation over 15 cm thickness. The removal cross‑section bound is therefore not a limiting constraint; the slowing‑down power is the correct metric.

