2.7 Chemistry Proof: Hydrogen Density from Polymer Chemistry

The hydrogen number density n_{\text{H}} in the composite is derived from the molecular structure of the polymer binder. Polyethylene (PE) has repeat unit -\text{CH}_2-\text{CH}_2-, molecular mass M_{\text{unit}} = 28\ \text{g/mol}, and contains 4 hydrogen atoms per unit. The number density of hydrogen in pure PE is

n_{\text{H,PE}} = \frac{4 \rho_{\text{PE}} N_A}{M_{\text{unit}}} = \frac{4 \times 0.95 \times 6.022\times10^{23}}{28} \approx 8.17\times10^{22}\ \text{cm}^{-3}.

In the composite with volume fraction \phi_{\text{PE}}, the hydrogen density from the polymer is n_{\text{H,poly}} = \phi_{\text{PE}} n_{\text{H,PE}}. The regolith also contains a small amount of hydrogen (chemically bound water, ~2 wt%), contributing n_{\text{H,reg}} \approx 0.02 \times \rho_{\text{reg}} N_A / M_{\text{H}} \approx 1.5\times10^{21}\ \text{cm}^{-3}. Total hydrogen density:

n_{\text{H,tot}} = \phi_{\text{PE}} \times 8.17\times10^{22} + 0.70 \times 1.5\times10^{21} .

For \phi_{\text{PE}}=0.30, n_{\text{H,tot}} \approx 2.45\times10^{22} + 1.05\times10^{21} = 2.56\times10^{22}\ \text{cm}^{-3}. This high hydrogen density is the physical origin of the large \Sigma_{t,n}.

