3.2 Proposition: Critical Shear‑Lag Length with Fatigue Degradation

Statement.
Efficient load transfer from matrix to regolith grains requires the grain length L to exceed the critical length l_c. Under Martian thermal cycling, the interfacial shear strength degrades, increasing l_c; nevertheless, typical processed regolith grains satisfy L > l_c at end of life.

Proof.
The shear‑lag model gives the critical length for a cylindrical inclusion of diameter d:

l_c = \frac{\sigma_{fu} \, d}{2 \tau_i},

where \sigma_{fu} is the tensile fracture strength of the regolith grain (≈100 MPa), and \tau_i is the interfacial shear strength between matrix and grain.

At beginning of life (BOL), with organosilane coupling agent, \tau_i^{\text{BOL}} = 10\ \text{MPa}. Hence

l_c^{\text{BOL}} = \frac{100 \times 50\ \mu\text{m}}{2 \times 10} = 250\ \mu\text{m}.

However, the Martian surface experiences diurnal temperature cycles of \Delta T \approx 170\ \text{K} (180 K to 290 K). The thermal expansion mismatch between polymer (\alpha_p \approx 150\times10^{-6}\ \text{K}^{-1}) and regolith (\alpha_r \approx 8\times10^{-6}\ \text{K}^{-1}) generates cyclic shear strain at the interface:

\Delta \varepsilon = (\alpha_p - \alpha_r) \Delta T \approx 142\times10^{-6} \times 170 = 0.02414.

The corresponding cyclic shear stress is \tau_{\text{cycle}} = G_m \Delta \varepsilon, where G_m = E_m / [2(1+\nu)] is the matrix shear modulus. With E_m=3\ \text{GPa}, \nu=0.4, G_m \approx 1.07\ \text{GPa}. Thus \tau_{\text{cycle}} \approx 1.07\times10^9 \times 0.02414 \approx 25.8\ \text{MPa}, exceeding the static strength. This leads to fatigue.

Empirical fatigue data for polymer‑silicate interfaces (Severin et al., 2015) follow a power‑law degradation:

\tau_i(N) = \tau_i^{\text{BOL}} \left( \frac{N_f}{N} \right)^{1/m},

with m \approx 10 and N_f the number of cycles to failure at the applied stress. For \tau_{\text{cycle}} = 25.8\ \text{MPa}, the initial N_f is small (≈10³ cycles). After N = 10^4 cycles (500 days × 20 cycles/day), the remaining strength is

\tau_i^{\text{EOL}} = 10 \times (10^3 / 10^4)^{0.1} = 10 \times (0.1)^{0.1} = 10 \times 0.794 \approx 7.94\ \text{MPa}.

Then the end‑of‑life critical length becomes

l_c^{\text{EOL}} = \frac{100 \times 50}{2 \times 7.94} \approx 315\ \mu\text{m}.

Sintered or compacted regolith grains in the composite have mean length L \approx 500–800\ \mu\text{m}. Since L > l_c^{\text{EOL}}, grain fracture occurs before pull‑out, ensuring efficient load transfer throughout the mission.

