3.3 Proposition: Pressure Vessel Hoop Stress Compliance

Statement.
The HRRC composite wall can withstand the hoop stress generated by 1 atm internal pressure with a safety factor > 25.

Proof.
Consider a cylindrical habitat of radius r = 2.5\ \text{m} and wall thickness t = 0.15\ \text{m}. The internal overpressure relative to Mars’ atmosphere is \Delta P \approx 100.7\ \text{kPa} (1 atm). The hoop stress is

\sigma_{\text{hoop}} = \frac{\Delta P \cdot r}{t} = \frac{100.7\times10^3 \times 2.5}{0.15} \approx 1.678\ \text{MPa}.

The composite’s tensile strength is governed by the matrix (since \phi_f is high and grains are well bonded). From the shear‑lag model, the ultimate tensile strength of the composite is

\sigma_{c,\text{ult}} = \sigma_m (1-\phi_f) + \sigma_{fu} \phi_f \left(1 - \frac{l_c}{2L}\right)

for L > l_c. With \sigma_m \approx 25\ \text{MPa} (polymer tensile strength), \phi_f = 0.7, l_c^{\text{EOL}} = 315\ \mu\text{m}, L = 600\ \mu\text{m} (average):

\sigma_{c,\text{ult}} = 25 \times 0.3 + 100 \times 0.7 \left(1 - \frac{315}{1200}\right) = 7.5 + 70 \times 0.7375 = 7.5 + 51.625 = 59.125\ \text{MPa}.

The safety factor is

\text{SF} = \frac{\sigma_{c,\text{ult}}}{\sigma_{\text{hoop}}} = \frac{59.125}{1.678} \approx 35.2,

well above the NASA requirement \text{SF} \ge 1.5.

