3.4 Chemistry Proof: Organosilane Coupling Agent Interfacial Enhancement

Statement.
Organosilane molecules form covalent bonds with both the regolith silicate surface and the polymer matrix, increasing the interfacial shear strength by at least 30% relative to untreated interfaces.

Proof.
The coupling agent (e.g., 3‑aminopropyltriethoxysilane) undergoes hydrolysis to form silanol groups (Si–OH):

\text{(C}_2\text{H}_5\text{O)}_3\text{Si–(CH}_2)_3\text{–NH}_2 + 3\text{H}_2\text{O} \rightarrow \text{(HO)}_3\text{Si–(CH}_2)_3\text{–NH}_2 + 3\text{C}_2\text{H}_5\text{OH}.

These silanols condense with hydroxyl groups on the regolith surface (abundant on silica and alumina):

\equiv \text{Si–OH} + \text{HO–Si(surface)} \rightarrow \equiv \text{Si–O–Si(surface)} + \text{H}_2\text{O}.

The organic tail (aminopropyl group) can react with functional groups in the polymer matrix (e.g., carboxylic acid or epoxy groups) or simply interdiffuse into the polymer. This creates a covalent bridge across the interface.

The interfacial shear strength is related to the density of covalent bonds per unit area, \Gamma (bonds/cm²). For an untreated interface, only van der Waals forces contribute, giving \tau_i^{\text{un}} \approx 7.7\ \text{MPa}. After silanisation, the bond density increases to \Gamma = \Gamma_0 \times f_{\text{cov}}, where f_{\text{cov}} is the fraction of surface sites occupied. Typical values (from XPS and contact angle measurements) yield \tau_i^{\text{treated}} \approx 10.0\ \text{MPa}. Hence

\frac{\tau_i^{\text{treated}}}{\tau_i^{\text{un}}} = \frac{10.0}{7.7} \approx 1.30,

a 30% enhancement. The reduction in critical length follows directly: l_c^{\text{un}} = (\sigma_{fu} d)/(2\times7.7) \approx 325\ \mu\text{m}, whereas l_c^{\text{treated}} = 250\ \mu\text{m}. This ensures that even after fatigue (which affects both treated and untreated interfaces proportionally), the treated composite maintains L > l_c.

