6.1 Proposition: Pareto Optimality of the HRRC Design Space

Statement.
The multi‑objective design space of HRRC parameters is compact and convex, guaranteeing the existence of a non‑empty Pareto front that simultaneously minimises mass, maximises neutron attenuation, and maximises structural strength.

Proof.
Define the design vector

\mathbf{x} = (\phi_{\text{PE}}, \rho_{\text{H}}, t_{\text{wall}}, \lambda_{\text{grad}})^T \in X \subset \mathbb{R}^4 ,

where \phi_{\text{PE}} is the polymer volume fraction, \rho_{\text{H}} the hydrogen number density, t_{\text{wall}} the shield thickness, and \lambda_{\text{grad}} a grading parameter for layered configurations. The feasible set X is compact (closed and bounded) and convex because each variable is bounded between physically admissible limits and the constraints are linear. The objective vector is

\mathbf{J}(\mathbf{x}) = \bigl( J_1(\mathbf{x}), J_2(\mathbf{x}), J_3(\mathbf{x}) \bigr) ,

with

· J_1 = m(\mathbf{x}) – total structural mass (to be minimised),
· J_2 = \Sigma_{t,\text{eff}}(\mathbf{x}) – effective neutron attenuation coefficient (to be maximised),
· J_3 = \sigma_{\text{comp}}(\mathbf{x}) – composite compressive strength (to be maximised).

Each J_i is continuous on X (from the analytical formulas in Chapters 2–4). By the Weierstrass extreme value theorem, each objective attains a minimum and maximum on X. Moreover, because the objectives are conflicting (e.g., increasing \phi_{\text{PE}} improves shielding but reduces strength), the set of Pareto‑optimal points

\mathcal{P} = \{ \mathbf{x} \in X \mid \nexists \mathbf{x}' \in X : J_i(\mathbf{x}') \ge J_i(\mathbf{x}) \text{ for all } i,\; J_j(\mathbf{x}') > J_j(\mathbf{x}) \text{ for some } j \}

is non‑empty. This follows from the Kuhn–Tucker conditions for multi‑objective optimisation when the objectives are continuous and X is compact.

Proposition proved.

Literature reference.
Active learning algorithms that directly use Pareto dominance have been shown to compute the set of Pareto‑optimal materials with high accuracy, even in high‑dimensional design spaces. For laminated composite structures, the determination of Pareto‑optimal curves has been tackled by analytical trade‑off methods transformed into design procedures. A 14‑dimensional compromise space was shown to capture every Pareto‑optimal performance while ensuring a bijective map to the design space.

