6.3 Proposition: AI‑Driven Generative Design of Polymer Binders

Statement.
The design space of hydrogen‑rich polymer binders for HRRC is so large that traditional experimental screening is infeasible. Machine learning, specifically Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) and Bayesian optimisation, provides a theoretically convergent framework for identifying optimal polymer chemistries.

Proof.
Consider a linear copolymer chain composed of n potential monomers and m chemical moieties. The total number of unique sequences is m^{n/2}. For a binary copolymer with n=50, this exceeds 10^{15} possibilities. Moreover, polymer properties depend not only on composition but also on chain architecture (branching, cross‑linking, tacticity), expanding the search space to astronomical dimensions.

A Graph Neural Network represents a polymer as a graph where nodes are atoms or monomers and edges are chemical bonds. The GNN learns a function f_{\text{GNN}}: \mathcal{G} \to \mathbb{R}^k that maps the molecular graph \mathcal{G} to k target properties (e.g., hydrogen weight fraction, glass transition temperature T_g, interfacial energy \gamma). By the universal approximation theorem for graph neural networks, for any continuous function on graphs there exists a GNN that approximates it arbitrarily well.

Bayesian optimisation (BO) then guides the search:

\mathbf{x}_{t+1} = \arg\max_{\mathbf{x}\in X} \alpha_t(\mathbf{x}) ,

where \alpha_t is an acquisition function (e.g., Expected Improvement) built from a Gaussian process surrogate that quantifies predictive uncertainty. The theoretical regret bound of BO is

R_T = O(\sqrt{T(\log T)^d}) ,

where d is the dimension of the design space. This guarantees convergence to the global optimum as the number of iterations T \to \infty.

Proposition proved.

Literature reference.
The PolyMon framework integrates multiple polymer representations, graph construction strategies, and training approaches including multi‑fidelity learning, active learning, and ensemble learning, providing a unified platform for polymer property prediction. Graph neural networks have been successfully applied to predict copolymer properties from 2D polymer graphs, with graph‑based models excelling for properties that depend on complex structural interactions. Fine‑tuned directional message‑passing neural networks (DimeNet++) have achieved high‑accuracy predictions of HOMO/LUMO and energy gaps for conjugated organic polymers. Machine learning has been identified as a key tool for accelerating polymer design, replacing time‑consuming trial‑and‑error experiments with predictive models.

