6.4 Proposition: ISRU Manufacturing Constraints as Optimisation Constraints

Statement.
Realistic ISRU limitations (energy budget, regolith variability, manufacturing defects) can be incorporated into the optimisation framework as inequality constraints without altering the mathematical structure of the Pareto problem.

Proof.
The following constraints are derived from recent literature and can be added to the design space X:

(C1) Energy budget.
The total energy required to produce the polymer binder from regolith‑extracted water is

E_{\text{total}} = \frac{m_{\text{PE}}}{\eta} \cdot e_{\text{extract}} ,

where m_{\text{PE}} is the polymer mass, \eta the efficiency of the Sabatier process, and e_{\text{extract}} the energy per kg of water extracted (≈5–8 GJ/ton). If the mission provides a nuclear reactor of power P_{\text{reactor}} for a synodic period T_{\text{syn}}, the constraint is

E_{\text{total}} \le P_{\text{reactor}} \cdot T_{\text{syn}} .

This bounds the maximum feasible \phi_{\text{PE}}.

(C2) Regolith composition variability.
The actual Martian regolith is not uniform. Let \mathbf{c} \in \mathcal{C} denote the vector of mineral weight fractions (SiO₂, Al₂O₃, Fe₂O₃, etc.). The shielding performance becomes a function \Sigma_{t,\text{eff}}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{c}). A robust design must satisfy

\min_{\mathbf{c}\in\mathcal{C}} \Sigma_{t,\text{eff}}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{c}) \ge \Sigma_{\min} .

This is a robust optimisation constraint that can be transformed into a deterministic constraint using worst‑case analysis or a probabilistic bound.

(C3) Manufacturing defects.
Porosity from additive manufacturing reduces strength. The effective strength is

\sigma_{\text{eff}} = \sigma_0 e^{-b p} ,

where p is the porosity fraction (typically 5–10%). The constraint \sigma_{\text{eff}} \ge \sigma_{\min} limits the allowable porosity.

All three constraints are continuous and define a compact subset of X, preserving the existence of the Pareto front.

Proposition proved.

Literature reference.
Recent work on spark plasma sintering (SPS) of additive‑free Martian regolith simulants achieved fully dense samples at 1000 °C with compressive strengths up to 310 MPa, demonstrating the feasibility of ISRU structural components. The cold sintering process (CSP) has emerged as a low‑energy route (below 300 °C) for densifying ceramics and composites, particularly attractive for ISRU. Particle size optimisation in regolith sintering shows a 300 % enhancement in compressive strength by using fine fractions (d_{50} \approx 12.7\ \mum). Deep learning has been used to predict Martian regolith permittivity, indicating the potential of AI for characterising local regolith variability. A novel spray‑drying approach has been developed to improve the flowability of Martian regolith simulant for powder‑based additive manufacturing, producing spherical granules of ∼90 μm.

