6.5 Proposition: Uncertainty Quantification via Bayesian Methods

Statement.
The uncertainties in regolith composition, cross‑section data, and manufacturing processes can be propagated through the analytical model using Bayesian inference, producing credible intervals for the predicted performance.

Proof.
Let the vector of uncertain parameters be \boldsymbol{\theta} = (\mathbf{c}, \boldsymbol{\sigma}, \mathbf{m}), where \mathbf{c} are mineral fractions, \boldsymbol{\sigma} are microscopic cross‑sections, and \mathbf{m} are manufacturing parameters (porosity, interfacial strength). The predictive distribution of the total dose equivalent is

p(D_{\text{total}} | \mathcal{D}) = \int p(D_{\text{total}} | \boldsymbol{\theta}) \, p(\boldsymbol{\theta} | \mathcal{D}) \, d\boldsymbol{\theta} ,

where \mathcal{D} represents all available prior information (ENDF/B‑VIII.0, regolith survey data, etc.). Using Bayes’ theorem:

p(\boldsymbol{\theta} | \mathcal{D}) = \frac{p(\mathcal{D} | \boldsymbol{\theta}) \, p(\boldsymbol{\theta})}{p(\mathcal{D})} .

When the posterior p(\boldsymbol{\theta} | \mathcal{D}) is intractable, Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods (e.g., Hamiltonian Monte Carlo) can generate samples. The 100(1-\alpha)\% credible interval for D_{\text{total}} is then obtained from the quantiles of the sampled distribution.

For large design spaces, Gaussian process (GP) surrogates can replace expensive forward evaluations, with the posterior mean and variance providing uncertainty estimates. The GP is fully defined by its mean function \mu(\mathbf{x}) and covariance kernel k(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x}'). The predictive variance at an unobserved point \mathbf{x}_* is

\sigma^2(\mathbf{x}_*) = k(\mathbf{x}_*,\mathbf{x}_*) - \mathbf{k}_*^T K^{-1} \mathbf{k}_* ,

quantifying the epistemic uncertainty due to limited data.

Proposition proved.

Literature reference.
Bayesian optimisation with Gaussian process surrogates has been successfully applied to polymer design, including constrained composite BO for guided synthesis of polymeric particles. A review of BO in polymer modelling highlights its use for coarse‑graining, electrolyte design, and autonomous inverse design. Mixed‑variable BO has been developed for emerging material systems including polymer nanocomposites.

