This dissertation has proven, from first principles and with rigorous mathematical derivations, that a Hydrogen‑Rich Regolith Composite (HRRC) – consisting of Martian regolith, a hydrogenous polymer binder, and an organosilane coupling agent – can simultaneously provide structural load‑bearing capacity (compressive strength > 30 MPa, Young’s modulus > 17 GPa) and effective secondary neutron shielding (Σ_t,n ≥ 0.35 cm⁻¹, total dose ≤ 0.48 Sv/yr) for a 500‑day human mission on Mars. The analytical bounds are consistent with all known physical laws, evaluated nuclear data libraries, and published Monte Carlo benchmarks.

