Appendix A: Derivation of Macroscopic Cross‑Section Additivity

A.1 Probability argument

Consider a composite composed of n phases, each with volume fraction \phi_i (\sum_i \phi_i = 1). Phase i has atomic number density N_i (atoms/cm³) and microscopic total cross‑section \sigma_t^{(i)}(E) at neutron energy E. Over an infinitesimal path length dx, the probability that a neutron interacts in phase i is the product of the probability that it is in phase i (which equals \phi_i for a randomly oriented, homogeneously mixed composite) and the probability of interaction while in that phase, which is \Sigma_i dx with \Sigma_i = N_i \sigma_t^{(i)}. Hence:

dP_i = \phi_i \Sigma_i dx .

Since the phases are non‑overlapping and interactions in different phases are mutually exclusive, the total interaction probability is the sum:

dP_{\text{total}} = \sum_{i=1}^n \phi_i \Sigma_i dx \equiv \Sigma_{\text{eff}} \, dx .

Thus

\boxed{\Sigma_{\text{eff}}(E) = \sum_{i=1}^n \phi_i \Sigma_i(E)} .

A.2 Mass‑fraction form

Let the composite have bulk density \rho_{\text{comp}} and mass fraction w_j of element j. The atomic number density of element j is N_j = \rho_{\text{comp}} w_j N_A / M_j, where N_A is Avogadro’s number and M_j the atomic mass. Then:

\Sigma_{\text{eff}} = \sum_j N_j \sigma_t^{(j)} = \rho_{\text{comp}} N_A \sum_j \frac{w_j}{M_j} \sigma_t^{(j)} .

This is the standard mixture rule.

A.3 Validation condition

The derivation assumes that the neutron mean free path \lambda_n = 1/\Sigma_{\text{eff}} is much larger than the characteristic inclusion size d. For fast neutrons (1–10 MeV) in hydrogenous materials, \lambda_n \approx 2–5 cm. In the HRRC, regolith grains have d \approx 50\ \mum, so d/\lambda_n \approx 10^{-3} – the condition is excellent. For thermal neutrons (0.025 eV), \lambda_n can be as low as 0.5 cm; then d/\lambda_n \approx 0.01, still acceptable. The only notable deviation occurs at strong resonances (e.g., iron at 1.15 eV), which we treat separately via self‑shielding (Appendix C).

