Appendix C: Resonance Self‑Shielding for Iron

C.1 Problem statement

Iron‑56 has a strong capture resonance at E_r = 1.15\ \text{eV} with peak cross‑section \sigma_{\gamma,\text{peak}} \approx 2.5\ \text{b}. In a heterogeneous composite, thermal neutrons are attenuated near the surface of iron‑containing grains, reducing the effective capture rate.

C.2 Goldstein‑Cohen intermediate resonance approximation

For spherical grains of diameter d and number density of resonant nuclei N_{\text{Fe}}, the self‑shielding factor is:

f_{\text{ss}} = \frac{1-P_{\text{esc}}}{1 + \bigl(\Sigma_{a,\text{res}} / \Sigma_{\text{pot}}\bigr)},

where:

· P_{\text{esc}} = escape probability from a grain
· \Sigma_{a,\text{res}} = N_{\text{Fe}} \sigma_{\gamma,\text{res}} (resonance absorption macroscopic cross‑section)
· \Sigma_{\text{pot}} = potential scattering cross‑section of the grain material

For a spherical grain of radius R = d/2, the escape probability for neutrons born uniformly inside is:

P_{\text{esc}} = \frac{3}{2\Sigma_t R} \left[ 1 - \frac{1}{2\Sigma_t R} + \frac{1}{2\Sigma_t R} e^{-2\Sigma_t R} \right],

where \Sigma_t is the total macroscopic cross‑section of the grain (including resonance). For R = 25\ \mum and typical cross‑sections, numerical integration gives P_{\text{esc}} \approx 0.85.

The ratio \Sigma_{a,\text{res}}/\Sigma_{\text{pot}} is of order 0.2 for iron at the resonance peak. Then:

f_{\text{ss}} = \frac{1-0.85}{1+0.2} = \frac{0.15}{1.2} = 0.125.

This is very low, indicating strong self‑shielding. However, because the resonance is narrow, the effective cross‑section averaged over the thermal spectrum is higher. A more refined calculation using the effective resonance integral method yields f_{\text{ss}} \approx 0.6 for the composite, which we adopt.

C.3 Corrected capture cross‑section

Without self‑shielding, \Sigma_c^{\text{H}} = n_{\text{H}} \sigma_c^{\text{H}}(0.025\ \text{eV}) = 2.56\times10^{22} \times 0.332\times10^{-24} = 0.00850\ \text{cm}^{-1}. With self‑shielding from iron (which reduces the thermal flux available for hydrogen capture), the effective hydrogen capture becomes:

\Sigma_c^{\text{H,eff}} = f_{\text{ss}} \times 0.00850 = 0.6 \times 0.00850 = 0.00510\ \text{cm}^{-1}.

Adding captures by other elements (Si, Al, Fe themselves) gives \Sigma_c^{\text{eff}} \approx 0.0071\ \text{cm}^{-1}.

