Appendix D: Halpin‑Tsai Model Derivation

D.1 General form

For a composite containing randomly oriented spherical particles, the Halpin‑Tsai equation is:

\frac{E_c}{E_m} = \frac{1 + \zeta \eta \phi_f}{1 - \eta \phi_f},
\qquad
\eta = \frac{E_f/E_m - 1}{E_f/E_m + \zeta},

where \zeta is a shape factor (\zeta=2 for spheres). This is derived from the self‑consistent micromechanics solution of Eshelby’s inclusion problem.

D.2 Derivation outline

Consider a single spherical inclusion of modulus E_f embedded in an infinite matrix of modulus E_m. The average stress and strain in the composite are related by the Mori‑Tanaka method. The resulting effective bulk modulus K_c and shear modulus G_c are given by:

K_c = K_m + \frac{\phi_f (K_f - K_m)}{1 + (1-\phi_f)\frac{K_f-K_m}{K_m + \frac{4}{3}G_m}},

G_c = G_m + \frac{\phi_f (G_f - G_m)}{1 + (1-\phi_f)\frac{G_f-G_m}{G_m + \frac{G_m(9K_m+8G_m)}{6(K_m+2G_m)}}}.

Then Young’s modulus is E_c = 9K_c G_c / (3K_c + G_c). The Halpin‑Tsai equation is an empirical approximation that matches this exact solution for a wide range of \phi_f.

D.3 Numerical values for HRRC

· E_f = 70\ \text{GPa} (regolith silicates)
· E_m = 3\ \text{GPa} (polyethylene)
· \phi_f = 0.7

Then E_f/E_m = 23.333, \eta = (23.333-1)/(23.333+2) = 22.333/25.333 = 0.882, and

E_c/E_m = (1+2\times0.882\times0.7)/(1-0.882\times0.7) = (1+1.2348)/(1-0.6174) = 2.2348/0.3826 = 5.842.

Thus E_c = 3 \times 5.842 = 17.53\ \text{GPa}.

