Appendix E: Shear‑Lag Model with Thermal Fatigue

E.1 Classical shear‑lag analysis

For a cylindrical fibre (or grain) of length L and diameter d, embedded in a matrix, the tensile stress in the fibre at position x from the end is:

\sigma_f(x) = \sigma_{fu} \left[ 1 - \frac{\cosh(\beta(L/2 - x))}{\cosh(\beta L/2)} \right],

where \beta = \sqrt{2G_m / (E_f r^2 \ln(R/r))} with r=d/2, R the matrix outer radius, and G_m the matrix shear modulus. The maximum stress occurs at the centre (x=L/2): \sigma_f^{\max} = \sigma_{fu} \left[1 - 1/\cosh(\beta L/2)\right]. For the fibre to fracture rather than pull out, we need \sigma_f^{\max} \ge \sigma_{fu}, which requires \beta L/2 \gg 1, i.e., L \ge l_c with

l_c = \frac{\sigma_{fu} d}{2 \tau_i},

where \tau_i is the interfacial shear strength (assumed constant). This is the critical length.

E.2 Thermal fatigue degradation

The thermal expansion mismatch generates a cyclic shear strain:

\Delta\gamma = (\alpha_p - \alpha_r) \Delta T.

For polyethylene (\alpha_p = 150\times10^{-6}\ \text{K}^{-1}), regolith (\alpha_r = 8\times10^{-6}\ \text{K}^{-1}), \Delta T = 170\ \text{K}, \Delta\gamma = 142\times10^{-6}\times170 = 0.02414. The corresponding cyclic shear stress in the matrix (if perfectly bonded) would be \tau_{\text{cycle}} = G_m \Delta\gamma = 1.07\ \text{GPa} \times 0.02414 = 25.8\ \text{MPa}. This exceeds the static strength, leading to interface damage.

From Severin et al. (2015), the degradation of interface strength under cyclic shear follows a power law:

\tau_i(N) = \tau_i(0) \left( \frac{N_f}{N} \right)^{1/m},

where N_f is the number of cycles to failure at the applied stress amplitude, and m \approx 10 for polymer‑silicate interfaces. For \tau_{\text{cycle}} = 25.8\ \text{MPa}, the initial life N_f is short (≈1000 cycles). After N = 10,000 cycles (500 days × 20 cycles/day):

\tau_i^{\text{EOL}} = 10 \times (1000/10000)^{0.1} = 10 \times 0.1^{0.1} = 10 \times 0.794 = 7.94\ \text{MPa}.

E.3 End‑of‑life critical length

l_c^{\text{EOL}} = \frac{100\ \text{MPa} \times 50\ \mu\text{m}}{2 \times 7.94\ \text{MPa}} = \frac{5000}{15.88} = 315\ \mu\text{m}.

Typical regolith grains after processing have L \approx 500–800\ \mu\text{m}, so L > l_c^{\text{EOL}} – pull‑out is avoided.

