Appendix F: Analytical Solution of Coupled Neutron‑Gamma Transport

F.1 Problem formulation

In one‑dimensional slab geometry, the neutron flux \phi_n(x) and gamma flux \phi_\gamma(x) satisfy:

\frac{d\phi_n}{dx} = -\Sigma_t \phi_n + S_n(x) \quad \text{(neutron transport)},

\frac{d\phi_\gamma}{dx} = -\mu \phi_\gamma + S_\gamma(x) \quad \text{(gamma transport)},

where the gamma source is S_\gamma(x) = \Sigma_c \phi_n(x), and S_n(x) includes the external GCR source at x=0 and scattering. For a purely absorbing shield (scattering neglected for simplicity), the solution for \phi_n(x) is:

\phi_n(x) = \phi_0 e^{-\Sigma_t x},

where \phi_0 is the incident neutron flux at the front surface. Then:

S_\gamma(x) = \Sigma_c \phi_0 e^{-\Sigma_t x}.

F.2 Gamma flux with buildup factor

The gamma transport equation including scattered photons via the buildup factor B is:

\phi_\gamma(x) = \int_0^x S_\gamma(x') \, B(\mu(x-x')) \, e^{-\mu(x-x')} dx'.

Substituting S_\gamma and assuming a constant average buildup factor \bar{B}:

\phi_\gamma(x) = \Sigma_c \phi_0 \bar{B} e^{-\mu x} \int_0^x e^{-(\Sigma_t - \mu)x'} dx'.

The integral is elementary:

\int_0^x e^{-(\Sigma_t - \mu)x'} dx' = \frac{1 - e^{-(\Sigma_t - \mu)x}}{\Sigma_t - \mu}, \quad \Sigma_t \neq \mu.

Thus:

\boxed{\phi_\gamma(x) = \frac{\Sigma_c \phi_0 \bar{B}}{\Sigma_t - \mu} e^{-\mu x} \left(1 - e^{-(\Sigma_t - \mu)x}\right)}.

F.3 Gamma dose rate

\dot{D}_\gamma(x) = \phi_\gamma(x) \cdot \frac{\mu_{\text{en}}}{\rho} \cdot E_\gamma \cdot \text{(conversion factors)}.

Using ICRP 103 fluence‑to‑dose coefficient C_\gamma (Sv·cm²):

\dot{D}_\gamma(x) = \phi_\gamma(x) \cdot C_\gamma.

F.4 Numerical example

With \Sigma_t = 0.35\ \text{cm}^{-1}, \mu = 0.10\ \text{cm}^{-1}, \Sigma_c = 0.0071\ \text{cm}^{-1}, \bar{B}=1.43, \phi_0^{\text{thermal}} = 0.05\ \text{cm}^{-2}\text{s}^{-1}, x=15\ \text{cm}:

\phi_\gamma = \frac{0.0071\times0.05\times1.43}{0.25} e^{-1.5} (1 - e^{-3.75}) = 2.03\times10^{-3} \times 0.2231 \times 0.9765 = 4.42\times10^{-4}\ \text{cm}^{-2}\text{s}^{-1}.

Then \dot{D}_\gamma = 4.42\times10^{-4} \times 3.2\times10^{-11} = 1.41\times10^{-14}\ \text{Sv/s} = 4.45\times10^{-7}\ \text{Sv/yr}, negligible.

