Appendix G: Arrhenius and Perchlorate Oxidation Mechanisms

G.1 Arrhenius derivation

The reaction rate constant for a thermally activated process is:

k(T) = A \exp\left(-\frac{E_a}{R T}\right).

Taking the ratio between two temperatures:

\frac{k(T_2)}{k(T_1)} = \exp\left[-\frac{E_a}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T_2} - \frac{1}{T_1}\right)\right].

For T_1 = 298\ \text{K} (Earth), T_2 = 210\ \text{K} (Mars), E_a = 80\ \text{kJ/mol}:

\frac{1}{210} - \frac{1}{298} = 0.0047619 - 0.0033557 = 0.0014062\ \text{K}^{-1},

\frac{E_a}{R} = \frac{80000}{8.314} = 9622\ \text{K},

-\frac{E_a}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T_2} - \frac{1}{T_1}\right) = -9622 \times 0.0014062 = -13.53,

k(210)/k(298) = e^{-13.53} = 1.32\times10^{-6}.

G.2 Perchlorate oxidation mechanism

The rate‑limiting step for perchlorate oxidation of an alkane (RH) is:

\text{ClO}_4^- + \text{RH} \rightarrow \text{ClO}_3^- + \text{R}^\cdot + \text{OH}^-.

The activation energy is high because the perchlorate ion is tetrahedrally symmetric and the O–Cl bond is strong (≈240 kJ/mol). Even with a large pre‑exponential factor A \approx 10^{12}\ \text{M}^{-1}\text{s}^{-1}, at 210 K:

k = 10^{12} \exp(-120000/(8.314\times210)) = 10^{12} \exp(-68.7) = 10^{12} \times 8.8\times10^{-30} = 8.8\times10^{-18}\ \text{M}^{-1}\text{s}^{-1}.

With a perchlorate concentration of ~0.1 M (typical in Martian soil water, but mostly frozen), the half‑life is t_{1/2} = \ln2/(k \cdot [\text{ClO}_4^-]) \approx 0.693 / (8.8\times10^{-18} \times 0.1) \approx 7.9\times10^{17}\ \text{s} \approx 2.5\times10^{10}\ \text{years}. Hence no measurable oxidation over a 500‑day mission.

