Appendix H: Langmuir Outgassing Derivation

H.1 Langmuir equation

The evaporation rate (mass flux) from a surface into vacuum is:

R = \alpha P_s \sqrt{\frac{M}{2\pi R_g T}},

where \alpha is the evaporation coefficient (≈0.8 for polymers), P_s the saturation vapour pressure of the volatile species, M the molecular weight, R_g the universal gas constant (8.314 J mol⁻¹ K⁻¹), and T the temperature.

H.2 Vapour pressure of polymer fragments

For cross‑linked polyethylene, the vapour pressure of oligomers (e.g., C₂H₄ units) at 210 K is extremely low. Literature data for polyethylene gives P_s < 10^{-7}\ \text{Pa} at 210 K (extrapolated from higher temperatures using Clausius‑Clapeyron).

H.3 Calculation

M = 0.028\ \text{kg/mol} (ethylene unit). Then:

\sqrt{\frac{M}{2\pi R_g T}} = \sqrt{\frac{0.028}{2\pi \times 8.314 \times 210}} = \sqrt{\frac{0.028}{10970}} = \sqrt{2.553\times10^{-6}} = 1.598\times10^{-3}\ \text{s/m}.

Thus R = 0.8 \times 10^{-7} \times 1.598\times10^{-3} = 1.278\times10^{-10}\ \text{kg/m}^2\text{s}.

Over 500 days (4.32\times10^7\ \text{s}): \Delta m = R \cdot T = 1.278\times10^{-10} \times 4.32\times10^7 = 5.52\times10^{-3}\ \text{kg/m}^2.

The wall areal density: thickness 15 cm, composite density \rho_{\text{comp}} \approx 1.6\ \text{g/cm}^3 → 150\ \text{cm} \times 1.6\ \text{g/cm}^3 = 240\ \text{g/cm}^2 = 2400\ \text{kg/m}^2. Wait, careful: 15 cm = 0.15 m, so areal mass = 0.15 m × 1600 kg/m³ = 240 kg/m². Earlier I used 1200 kg/m² incorrectly. Correct:

\frac{\Delta m}{m_0} = \frac{5.52\times10^{-3}}{240} = 2.30\times10^{-5}.

Still far below the ASTM E595 limit of 0.01 (1%).

