Appendix L: Proof of Pareto Optimality Existence

L.1 Definitions

Let X \subset \mathbb{R}^n be the feasible design space, compact (closed and bounded) and convex. Let F: X \to \mathbb{R}^m be a vector of objective functions, each continuous on X. A point \mathbf{x}^* \in X is Pareto optimal if there does not exist another \mathbf{x} \in X such that F_i(\mathbf{x}) \ge F_i(\mathbf{x}^*) for all i and F_j(\mathbf{x}) > F_j(\mathbf{x}^*) for at least one j.

L.2 Existence theorem

Because X is compact and each F_i is continuous, the set F(X) is compact in \mathbb{R}^m. Consider the set of non‑dominated points in F(X). Since F(X) is closed and bounded, its Pareto frontier is non‑empty. This follows from the fact that the partial order \preceq (component‑wise) on \mathbb{R}^m is a closed order, and the maximum of a continuous scalarisation (e.g., \sum w_i F_i with w_i>0) attains a maximum on X. That maximum is Pareto optimal.

L.3 Application to HRRC

Our design space X = [\phi_{\text{PE,min}},\phi_{\text{PE,max}}] \times [\rho_{\text{H,min}},\rho_{\text{H,max}}] \times [t_{\text{min}},t_{\text{max}}] is a hyperrectangle, hence compact and convex. The objectives J_1 = m(\mathbf{x}) (mass), J_2 = \Sigma_{t,\text{eff}}(\mathbf{x}) (attenuation), J_3 = \sigma_{\text{comp}}(\mathbf{x}) (strength) are continuous (from Chapters 2–3). Therefore a Pareto front exists.

